Can anything be expedient, then, which is con- trary to such a chorus of virtues? And yet the Cyrenaics, adherents of the school of Aristippus, and the philosophers who bear the name of Anni- ceris find all good to consist in pleasure and consider virtue praiseworthy only because it is productive of pleasure. Now that these schools are out of date, Epicurus has come into vogue—an advocate and supporter of practically the same doctrine. Against such a philosophy we must fight it out “with horse and foot,'’ as the saying is, if our, purpose is to defend and maintain our standard of moral rectitude.
